First, we can use the identity $\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1$ to rewrite the expression:

\begin{align*}
&\sin^3 2x \cos 6x + \cos^3 2x \sin 6x \\
=& (\sin^2 2x + \cos^2 2x) \sin 2x \cos 6x + (\cos^2 2x + \sin^2 2x) \cos 2x \sin 6x
\end{align*}

To simplify this expression, we can use the identity $\sin x \cos y = \frac{1}{2}(\sin(x+y)+\sin(x-y))$ twice:

\begin{align*}
&= \frac{1}{2}\left[\sin(2x+6x) + \sin(2x-6x)\right] + \frac{1}{2}\left[\sin(2x+6x) - \sin(2x-6x)\right]\\
=&\frac{1}{2}(\sin 8x+\sin(-4x)) + \frac{1}{2}(\sin 8x-\sin(-4x))\\
=&\frac{1}{2}\left[2\sin 8x\right] = \boxed{\sin 8x}
\end{align*}

Therefore, $a=1$ and $b=8$, so $a+b=\boxed{9}$.

